diamonds, spades here,

00:16:36.396 --> 00:16:38.263
it's still gonna be one-seventeenth.

00:16:38.263 --> 00:16:43.425
And yet here, where we didn't specify it,
it's 1 over 33.

00:16:45.791 --> 00:16:50.060
So I'm gonna let you think
about this problem for a while.

00:16:50.060 --> 00:16:52.340
This is a problem that
you could spend hours and

00:16:52.340 --> 00:16:55.410
hours trying to build intuition about.

00:16:56.920 --> 00:16:59.698
I'm mainly doing it just for
practice with the definition.

00:16:59.698 --> 00:17:02.100
And to show you that even
something that sounds,

00:17:02.100 --> 00:17:04.450
this sounds like a very simple problem,
okay?

00:17:04.450 --> 00:17:07.622
But already something very
surprising is going on here.

00:17:07.622 --> 00:17:11.380
So conditional probability can be very,
very subtle.

00:17:11.380 --> 00:17:13.874
One hint for thinking about it is,

00:17:13.874 --> 00:17:18.618
here we're saying we have an ace
that means at least one, right?

00:17:18.618 --> 00:17:22.040
Now here, well we could say we have
at least one Ace of Spades, but

00:17:22.040 --> 00:17:24.090
if we say there's at
least one Ace of Spades,

00:17:24.090 --> 00:17:26.840
we're just saying we have the Ace of
Spades cuz there's only one Ace of Spades.

00:17:26.840 --> 00:17:31.910
So here I can specifically say, here I
have the Ace of Spades, something else.

00:17:31.910 --> 00:17:34.230
Here, it's complicated.

00:17:34.230 --> 00:17:37.184
I can't draw the same
picture here as there,

00:17:37.184 --> 00:17:40.619
because I'm just saying
there's at least one ace.

00:17:40.619 --> 00:17:45.508
So there's a difference here in terms
of talking about at least one or

00:17:45.508 --> 00:17:46.696
a specific one.

00:17:46.696 --> 00:17:52.792
All right, so that's just a fun problem to
think about with conditional probability.

00:17:52.792 --> 00:17:55.173
Let's do another example.

00:17:55.173 --> 00:17:59.387
This kind of thing actually
is important in gambling, but

00:17:59.387 --> 00:18:02.827
let's do one that's
important in daily life.

00:18:02.827 --> 00:18:08.478
So, suppose that we're testing for
a disease.

00:18:12.470 --> 00:18:16.816
So this is a problem
that comes up every day

00:18:16.816 --> 00:18:21.670
everywhere in the world
in a medical context.

00:18:21.670 --> 00:18:27.507
So suppose that a patient comes in, and
is getting tested for a certain disease.

00:18:32.169 --> 00:18:36.048
Okay, this is a good problem and
just illustrating.

00:18:38.248 --> 00:18:41.329
You have to think very carefully
about what your conditioning on,

00:18:41.329 --> 00:18:42.750
what's your goal?

00:18:42.750 --> 00:18:44.800
And that's a hint for

00:18:44.800 --> 00:18:50.250
the homework as well to try to clearly
specify what are you trying to find.

00:18:50.250 --> 00:18:53.340
Make up some clear notation and
then say very,

00:18:53.340 --> 00:18:59.290
very explicitly, our goal is to find p
of what given what, that kind of thing.

00:18:59.290 --> 00:19:01.289
Okay, so patient gets tested for disease.

00:19:01.289 --> 00:19:07.892
And suppose that that particular disease
afflicts 1% of the population or

00:19:07.892 --> 00:19:13.978
maybe wanna say, 1% of people who
are similar in demographically,

00:19:13.978 --> 00:19:17.194
same age, and so on as this patient.

00:19:17.194 --> 00:19:23.607
1% of similar patients have the disease,

00:19:23.607 --> 00:19:28.974
okay, that's the assumption.

00:19:28.974 --> 00:19:33.290
And suppose that the patient tests
positive, that's the result.

00:19:33.290 --> 00:19:38.020
And even though testing positive
sounds good, that's actually bad.

00:19:38.020 --> 00:19:41.010
Tests positive means that the test

00:19:41.010 --> 00:19:43.660
is asserting that
the patient has the disease.

00:19:43.660 --> 00:19:45.840
Now, the test could be wrong, right?

00:19:45.840 --> 00:19:50.949
But if the test is correct, then that
means the patient has the disease, okay?

00:19:50.949 --> 00:19:52.893
So that's what a positive test means.

00:19:52.893 --> 00:19:58.187
Now, so far I haven't said anything
about how reliable is the test, right?

00:19:58.187 --> 00:20:00.790
So some diseases are hard to detect, okay?

00:20:00.790 --> 00:20:05.088
And so some diseases are easy to detect,
some are hard to detect.

00:20:05.088 --> 00:20:08.480
And some tests work better
than other tests, right?

00:20:08.480 --> 00:20:10.607
Okay, so we need some assumption there.

00:20:10.607 --> 00:20:13.347
And so
suppose that the test is advertised,

00:20:17.938 --> 00:20:20.840
As being 95% accurate.

00:20:20.840 --> 00:20:24.014
You might see some marketing
that the people who

00:20:24.014 --> 00:20:28.786
manufacture this particular test and
they say it's 95% accurate.

00:20:28.786 --> 00:20:29.924
And what does that actually mean?

00:20:29.924 --> 00:20:32.422
I"m putting that in quotes
because that's not yet

00:20:32.422 --> 00:20:35.280
precise enough to actually
do anything with.

00:20:35.280 --> 00:20:40.400
So we're gonna have to interpret what
does it mean for it to be 95% accurate?

00:20:40.400 --> 00:20:43.520
There's more than one ways you
can interpret that phrase.

00:20:43.520 --> 00:20:45.210
That's ambiguous right now.

00:20:45.210 --> 00:20:49.536
So to be able to solve the problem
I'm gonna make a specific assumption.

00:20:49.536 --> 00:20:54.294
So suppose, that's an assumption,
that this means,

00:20:56.947 --> 00:21:00.304
Now we start needing some notation for
the different events.

00:21:02.180 --> 00:21:04.780
So let's define our events here.

00:21:04.780 --> 00:21:08.430
Let's let D be the event that
the patient has the disease.

00:21:09.780 --> 00:21:13.165
Patient has disease, D for disease.

00:21:18.382 --> 00:21:23.160
Okay, when you're defining events, try to
write it out as carefully as possible.

00:21:23.160 --> 00:21:28.300
It will be tempting here to
just write D for disease, okay?

00:21:28.300 --> 00:21:30.040
But that's confusing, right?

00:21:30.040 --> 00:21:31.379
Disease is not an event.

00:21:31.379 --> 00:21:33.679
The event is that
the patient has a disease.

00:21:33.679 --> 00:21:38.121
Now if it's very obvious in the context
what you mean, then that's fine, but

00:21:38.121 --> 00:21:42.628
a lot of times, if you're just writing
down, B is blood, and D is disease and so

00:21:42.628 --> 00:21:44.810
on, and they're not really events.

00:21:44.810 --> 00:21:48.257
It's gonna be very confusing for anyone
to understand what you're doing, okay?

00:21:48.257 --> 00:21:49.601
So, D is the event that this patient,

00:21:49.601 --> 00:21:52.123
we're assuming we have a specific
patient that we're talking about.

00:21:52.123 --> 00:21:55.998
That patient has the disease,
that's event D.

00:21:55.998 --> 00:22:00.420
And let's let T be the event
that the patient tests positive.

00:22:00.420 --> 00:22:03.693
I would normally wanna use P for positive,
but it's very confusing to use P for

00:22:03.693 --> 00:22:05.095
probability and P for positive.

00:22:05.095 --> 00:22:07.309
So don't call your events P, okay?

00:22:07.309 --> 00:22:09.557
So I'll just say patient tests positive.

00:22:13.866 --> 00:22:17.349
Okay, so
those are our two events that we need.

00:22:17.349 --> 00:22:20.142
I don't think we need any
more notation at this point.

00:22:20.142 --> 00:22:25.462
So let's suppose that 95% accurate means

00:22:25.462 --> 00:22:30.642
that the probability of T given D = 0.95

00:22:30.642 --> 00:22:37.226
= the probability of T
complement given D complement.

00:22:37.226 --> 00:22:39.354
So that's an assumption.

00:22:39.354 --> 00:22:40.674
What this assumption is?

00:22:40.674 --> 00:22:42.824
So that's an interpretation
of 95% accurate.

00:22:42.824 --> 00:22:45.882
And what this says,
is if the patient has the disease,

00:22:45.882 --> 00:22:50.540
then 95% of the time that the test
will correctly report test positive.

00:22:50.540 --> 00:22:52.791
If the patient does not have the disease,

00:22:52.791 --> 00:22:56.344
then 95% of the time the test
will correctly report negative.

00:22:56.344 --> 00:22:59.728
So conditional on whether
the patient has the disease or not,

00:22:59.728 --> 00:23:02.665
95% of the time the test
gives the correct answer.

00:23:02.665 --> 00:23:04.026
Does that make sense?

00:23:04.026 --> 00:23:06.031
So that's the assumption, okay.

00:23:06.031 --> 00:23:10.162
But that's not actually
what we want to know.

00:23:10.162 --> 00:23:13.182
What do you think the patient cares about?

00:23:13.182 --> 00:23:15.170
The patient doesn't care about that.

00:23:15.170 --> 00:23:20.750
The patient wants to know whether he or
she has the disease, right?

00:23:20.750 --> 00:23:25.746
So what the patient cares
about is not P of T given D,

00:23:25.746 --> 00:23:28.640
it's P of D given T, okay?

00:23:28.640 --> 00:23:29.743
So that's our goal.

00:23:29.743 --> 00:23:35.289
Our goal is to find P of D given T.

00:23:35.289 --> 00:23:40.995
Now, so one of the most common
mistakes in statistics as applied

00:23:40.995 --> 00:23:45.980
in real life is confusing P of
T given D with P of D given T.

00:23:45.980 --> 00:23:47.940
Although they're completely
different concepts.

00:23:47.940 --> 00:23:50.880
Luckily, we know how they're connected,
right?

00:23:50.880 --> 00:23:54.170
We don't just ever say this
is different from this,

00:23:54.170 --> 00:23:55.625
we actually know how they're related.

00:23:55.625 --> 00:23:57.868
They're related by Bayes rule, right?

00:23:57.868 --> 00:24:00.350
So a Bayes rule, what does that say?

00:24:00.350 --> 00:24:06.434
Bayes' rule says P(D given T)
is P(T given D)P(D) over P(T).

00:24:07.906 --> 00:24:13.632
That's just Bayes' rule,
which we proved in one line Wednesday or

00:24:13.632 --> 00:24:16.900
Monday, that's Bayes' rule.

00:24:16.900 --> 00:24:21.260
And we already know P(D given T),
we know P(D), that's just for

00:24:21.260 --> 00:24:23.780
the populations, that's 0.01.

00:24:23.780 --> 00:24:30.120
The ony thing left is P(T), we don't yet
know P(T), so here's a little trick.

00:24:31.520 --> 00:24:34.780
And sometimes if you look in books
they won't state Bayes' rule this way.

00:24:34.780 --> 00:24:37.870
They'll do something more complicated
with the sum in the denominator.

00:24:37.870 --> 00:24:41.780
But I don't consider that Bayes' rule,
this is Bayes' rule.

00:24:41.780 --> 00:24:45.154
Okay, and now often the denominator
is the tricky part, and for

00:24:45.154 --> 00:24:49.110
doing the denominator, that's when
we do this law of total probability.

00:24:49.110 --> 00:24:53.489
Okay, so
it's very common to use Bayes' rule and

00:24:53.489 --> 00:24:57.050
the law of total probability in tandem.

00:24:57.050 --> 00:25:03.204
So if we expand the denominator using
the law of total probability, well,

00:25:03.204 --> 00:25:10.840
that's just gonna be P(T given D)P(D) +
P(T given D complement)P(D complement).

00:25:10.840 --> 00:25:13.197
So our partition is a very obvious one,

00:25:13.197 --> 00:25:17.126
the partition is just saying either
the patient has the disease or

00:25:17.126 --> 00:25:21.410
does not have the disease, so
breaking up into those two cases.

00:25:21.410 --> 00:25:24.360
Right, so it's hard to
immediately see what P(T) is, but

00:25:24.360 --> 00:25:27.040
it's easy as soon as we
break into two cases.

00:25:27.040 --> 00:25:32.150
So we have two cases, it's kind of neat
also that this thing in the numerator,

00:25:32.150 --> 00:25:34.230
when we write it this way,
it's the same thing here.

00:25:34.230 --> 00:25:38.072
And then plus the case where D complement,
it kind of has a nice structure to it.

00:25:38.072 --> 00:25:40.900
All right, so at this point,
we know all of these numbers,

00:25:40.900 --> 00:25:41.910
we can just plug them in.

00:25:41.910 --> 00:25:48.190
I guess I didn't mention, let's see,
what's P(T given D complement)?

00:25:48.190 --> 00:25:52.610
Well, we know P(T complement
given D complement) is 0.95, so

00:25:52.610 --> 00:25:56.440
therefore P(T given D complement) is 0.05,
right?

00:25:56.440 --> 00:26:01.139
Cuz given, it's just the complement, so

00:26:01.139 --> 00:26:07.541
if you plug all that in,
you get approximately 0.16.

00:26:10.110 --> 00:26:15.272
So even though the test is supposedly
95% accurate in this sense,

00:26:15.272 --> 00:26:20.410
there's only a 16% chance that
the patient has the disease.

00:26:20.410 --> 00:26:25.030
And that seems surprising both to most
patients and to most doctors at first.

00:26:25.030 --> 00:26:29.398
And in fact, there was a study
Done at Harvard where they asked

00:26:29.398 --> 00:26:34.366
something like 60 Harvard doctors
a question very similar to this.

00:26:34.366 --> 00:26:37.999
And something like 80% of the doctors, and

00:26:37.999 --> 00:26:42.950
they were basically asked to
guess what should this number be.

00:26:42.950 --> 00:26:46.834
And 80% of the doctors said
numbers like 95% or very,

00:26:46.834 --> 00:26:50.881
very high numbers, and
didn't realize that it was so small.

00:26:55.572 --> 00:26:59.209
So what's the moral of the story,
one thing is,

00:26:59.209 --> 00:27:04.410
you should get a second opinion,
right, do another test.

00:27:04.410 --> 00:27:06.910
And there's some subtleties
that come up there too,

00:27:06.910 --> 00:27:10.290
because maybe the second test is
not independent of the first test.

00:27:10.290 --> 00:27:13.040
In that if there was something that was
causing the test to be wrong the first

00:27:13.040 --> 00:27:15.110
time, maybe the same
thing would happen again.

00:27:15.110 --> 00:27:16.910
So it'd be a good idea to get
a different kind of test.

00:27:18.190 --> 00:27:20.630
Secondly, what's really going on here,

00:27:22.630 --> 00:27:26.660
most people's intuition on this
problem is completely wrong.

00:27:26.660 --> 00:27:28.105
Maybe they guess 95%, or

00:27:28.105 --> 00:27:31.560
maybe they would conservatively
lower it down to 70% or 80%.

00:27:31.560 --> 00:27:35.080
But hardly anyone,
if you ask this problem, will say 16%.

00:27:35.080 --> 00:27:39.420
So why is people's intuition so
completely wrong about this?

00:27:39.420 --> 00:27:44.450
Well, I think the reason is that they
focus on this part of the problem.

00:27:44.450 --> 00:27:48.840
But an equally important part
of the problem is this 1% here,

00:27:48.840 --> 00:27:50.640
and that's what gets ignored.

00:27:52.450 --> 00:27:56.970
So there's a tradeoff here,
it's fairly rare

00:27:56.970 --> 00:28:02.290
that the test is wrong, but it's also
fairly rare that someone has the disease.

00:28:02.290 --> 00:28:06.270
So there's kind of a competition
between how rare is the disease

00:28:06.270 --> 00:28:08.940
versus how rarely is the test wrong.

00:28:08.940 --> 00:28:10.731
And for some psychological reason,

00:28:10.731 --> 00:28:13.513
most people focus on the part
about the test being wrong.

00:28:13.513 --> 00:28:17.340
And don't focus on the fact that
the disease itself is rare.

00:28:17.340 --> 00:28:19.640
So most people's intuition
is wrong because of that.

00:28:19.640 --> 00:28:24.350
Here's another, just if you want another
quick intuition into this problem.

00:28:24.350 --> 00:28:27.230
Remember we talked about
frequentists' world last time?

00:28:27.230 --> 00:28:30.280
Where we were repeating the same
experiment over and over again, so

00:28:30.280 --> 00:28:32.540
suppose we didn't just do
this with one patient.

00:28:32.540 --> 00:28:34.410
Suppose we had 1000,
I'm not going to write this,

00:28:34.410 --> 00:28:36.360
I'm just giving you a quick intuition.

00:28:37.400 --> 00:28:40.738
Suppose we repeated this 1000 times,
as we have 1000 patients.

00:28:40.738 --> 00:28:43.967
And just speaking roughly,
if we have 1000 patients,

00:28:43.967 --> 00:28:47.530
about 10 of them will have the disease,
right, that's 1%.

00:28:47.530 --> 00:28:52.118
Maybe not exactly 10, but just roughly,
intuitively speaking, we'd imagine,

00:28:52.118 --> 00:28:55.000
1000 patients, 10 have the disease.

00:28:55.000 --> 00:28:59.098
And let's suppose that for those 10,
the test is correct every time, so

00:28:59.098 --> 00:29:00.865
all 10 of them test positive.

00:29:00.865 --> 00:29:05.130
Now what about the other 900 and
whatever people?

00:29:05.130 --> 00:29:10.000
10 people have the disease, so
990 people do not have the disease.

00:29:10.000 --> 00:29:17.580
They all get tested, but something like 5%
of those people are gonna test positive.

00:29:17.580 --> 00:29:21.500
Just roughly speaking in that example,
I'm not gonna compute exact numbers,

00:29:21.500 --> 00:29:22.730
I'm just giving you some intuition.

00:29:23.800 --> 00:29:26.607
Roughly speaking, 50,
that's 5% of 1000, so

00:29:26.607 --> 00:29:30.114
about 50 people would test positive
who don't have the disease, and

00:29:30.114 --> 00:29:33.560
about 10 people would test
positive who do have the disease.

00:29:33.560 --> 00:29:37.664
So that's in a ratio of 5 to 1,
and 0.16 is about one-sixth,

00:29:37.664 --> 00:29:39.472
so that's what's going on.

00:29:39.472 --> 00:29:42.310
You have 50 people who tested positive
who don't have the disease, and

00:29:42.310 --> 00:29:43.408
10 who did, question?

00:29:43.408 --> 00:29:50.109
&gt;&gt; [INAUDIBLE]
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

00:29:50.109 --> 00:29:55.366
&gt;&gt; [INAUDIBLE]
&gt;&gt; Yeah,

00:29:55.366 --> 00:29:57.970
so that is an extremely
important question.

00:29:57.970 --> 00:30:00.952
In case anyone couldn't hear, the question
is, will they usually be higher?

00:30:00.952 --> 00:30:03.499
Because if the patient
who's getting tested,

00:30:03.499 --> 00:30:07.890
maybe they came in because they
are having symptoms and things like that.

00:30:07.890 --> 00:30:13.580
So the calculation would completely change
if that patient already has information,

00:30:13.580 --> 00:30:16.900
like certain symptoms that
are consistent with the disease.

00:30:16.900 --> 00:30:20.264
The calculation would change,
but the principle is the same.

00:30:20.264 --> 00:30:23.153
The principle is whatever evidence,
you have some initial, so

00:30:23.153 --> 00:30:25.730
maybe it's initially 1% if
don't have any evidence.

00:30:25.730 --> 00:30:29.244
As you start getting symptoms,
then that's evidence,

00:30:29.244 --> 00:30:31.520
and you update your probabilities.

00:30:31.520 --> 00:30:34.880
And maybe this 1% would
change to something higher,

00:30:34.880 --> 00:30:38.090
and that would change the numbers around.

00:30:38.090 --> 00:30:40.780
But the principle is the same,
you get evidence and

00:30:40.780 --> 00:30:44.020
you update your probabilities
using Bayes' rule.

00:30:44.020 --> 00:30:47.060
And here's one really crucial and

00:30:47.060 --> 00:30:51.390
beautiful fact about Bayes' rule,
it has a certain coherency property.

00:30:52.660 --> 00:30:57.570
And I kinda work out the math of this in
one of the strategic practice problems,

00:30:57.570 --> 00:30:59.410
but let me just tell you
the intuition right now.

00:31:00.520 --> 00:31:06.050
Suppose that you get two pieces of
evidence, not just one, suppose you

00:31:06.050 --> 00:31:10.840
are investigating a crime and
there's two possibilities.

00:31:10.840 --> 00:31:12.674
Either you get two clues and

00:31:12.674 --> 00:31:18.193
you update using Bayes' rule using the
intersection of those two events, okay?

00:31:18.193 --> 00:31:23.123
But another possibility would be,
you get one clue, and then you go off and

00:31:23.123 --> 00:31:25.010
get lunch and take a break.

00:31:25.010 --> 00:31:27.880
You come back after lunch,
you get another clue, okay?

00:31:27.880 --> 00:31:30.990
So suppose that you updated your
probabilities using the first clue,

00:31:30.990 --> 00:31:34.470
and then you come back later and
get the second clue, update again.

00:31:34.470 --> 00:31:39.348
You'll get the same thing, so as long as,
so you can update it more than one step,

00:31:39.348 --> 00:31:40.990
you can update all at once.

00:31:40.990 --> 00:31:46.280
You can update in either order, it's
always gonna be completely consistent.

00:31:46.280 --> 00:31:51.509
So Bayes' rule is coherent in that sense,
that whatever evidence you get,

00:31:51.509 --> 00:31:55.203
one piece at a time or
all at once or some combination.

00:31:55.203 --> 00:31:57.980
The end result is gonna
be what's the probability

00:31:57.980 --> 00:32:01.560
of the thing you're interested
in given the evidence you have.

00:32:03.230 --> 00:32:05.486
So that's really nice.

00:32:05.486 --> 00:32:10.472
So just a couple quick
warnings about common mistakes

00:32:10.472 --> 00:32:13.580
with conditional probability.

00:32:13.580 --> 00:32:19.458
And then we can do another example, So

00:32:19.458 --> 00:32:23.609
I call these biohazards,
basically just common mistakes.

00:32:23.609 --> 00:32:26.634
But they are hazardous to your
health if you make them, so

00:32:26.634 --> 00:32:28.710
you have to be really careful.

00:32:28.710 --> 00:32:32.350
These are common mistakes
with conditional probability.

00:32:32.350 --> 00:32:36.518
So 1 is the one we just talked about,

00:32:36.518 --> 00:32:40.964
confusing P(A|B) with P(B|A).

00:32:45.801 --> 00:32:48.732
And we know that Bayes' rule is
how you can connect these two, but

00:32:48.732 --> 00:32:50.360
they're not the same thing.

00:32:50.360 --> 00:32:52.870
Sometimes this is called
