00:33:04.928 --> 00:33:09.134
Doctor's make the same mistake, people
make that mistake all the time in everyday

00:33:09.134 --> 00:33:11.820
life, so
it's unfair to just pick on prosecutors.

00:33:11.820 --> 00:33:16.363
The reason it's called
the prosecutor's fallacy is that it's

00:33:16.363 --> 00:33:18.221
a common situation that.

00:33:18.221 --> 00:33:20.861
And maybe sometimes the prosecutor
does it deliberately, and

00:33:20.861 --> 00:33:23.690
maybe sometimes it's cuz
they don't know this stuff.

00:33:23.690 --> 00:33:28.689
But it's the mistake of,
if you're deciding a criminal case,

00:33:28.689 --> 00:33:33.319
what you care about is
the probability that the defendant is

00:33:33.319 --> 00:33:36.480
guilty given all the evidence, right?

00:33:36.480 --> 00:33:40.858
And the mistake would be focusing entirely
on the probability of the evidence,

00:33:40.858 --> 00:33:41.913
given innocence.

00:33:41.913 --> 00:33:45.944
And you want the probability of
innocence given evidence, right, so

00:33:45.944 --> 00:33:47.800
those two things get confused.

00:33:49.341 --> 00:33:52.292
Let me mention one legal example,

00:33:52.292 --> 00:33:58.200
which is a very sad true story
called the Sally Clark case.

00:33:58.200 --> 00:34:02.930
This is an extreme example, but there are
many other legal cases that are similar in

00:34:02.930 --> 00:34:08.810
flavor, in varying degrees,
similar in spirit to this one.

00:34:08.810 --> 00:34:12.540
This is an especially sad, true story.

00:34:12.540 --> 00:34:17.410
So Sally Clark was a British
woman who had, two of her babies

00:34:17.410 --> 00:34:22.390
