00:38:48.940 --> 00:38:53.713
So the second mistake is confusing P(A),

00:38:53.713 --> 00:38:56.680
that's called the prior.

00:38:58.210 --> 00:39:03.410
Prior means before we have evidence,
posterior means after we have evidence.

00:39:05.110 --> 00:39:12.110
With P(A|B),
which is called the posterior.

00:39:16.178 --> 00:39:20.609
So one instance of that is,
sometimes students,

00:39:20.609 --> 00:39:23.984
if the problem says that A occurs, and

00:39:23.984 --> 00:39:28.743
then they would be very
tempted to write P(A) = 1.

00:39:28.743 --> 00:39:32.293
And I ask, why did you write P(A) = 1?

00:39:32.293 --> 00:39:36.578
And the student says,
because it's given that A occurred, okay?

00:39:36.578 --> 00:39:40.852
But that's completely wrong and
leads to completely wrong arguments.

00:39:40.852 --> 00:39:48.768
P(A|A) =1,
that's the key thing to keep in mind.

00:39:48.768 --> 00:39:52.074
That's always gonna be true,
given that A occurred, P(A) = 1.

00:39:52.074 --> 00:39:55.890
But if we just write the P(A),
we're not assuming that.

00:39:55.890 --> 00:39:58.680
So the problem they say we
observe that they occurred and

00:39:58.680 --> 00:40:02.380
that's saying we're interested
in computing stuff given A but

00:40:02.380 --> 00:40:05.750
doesn't mean just write P(A)=1,
P(A) given A is 1.

00:40:05.750 --> 00:40:09.280
So when you're writing down conditional
probability calculations you have to very,

00:40:09.280 --> 00:40:13.290
very careful about what should you
put to the left of this bar and

00:40:13.290 --> 00:40:17.800
what do you put to the right of this bar,
okay?

00:40:19.180 --> 00:40:26.130
And one more common mistake
with probability is confusing

00:40:26.130 --> 00:40:34.210
independence with
conditional independence.

00:40:34.210 --> 00:40:37.120
And I haven't yet defined the term
conditional independence, so

00:40:37.120 --> 00:40:38.230
I'll do that now.

00:40:38.230 --> 00:40:41.560
But I'm actually kind of assuming that
you already understand what conditional

00:40:41.560 --> 00:40:43.050
independence means.

00:40:43.050 --> 00:40:44.690
That is,
you should be able to guess what it means.

00:40:44.690 --> 00:40:45.690
I'll write it down.

00:40:45.690 --> 00:40:48.170
And you can see if that
agrees with your guess.

00:40:48.170 --> 00:40:51.920
Confusing independence with
conditional independence.

00:40:53.420 --> 00:40:57.920
This is a more subtle mistake
than these first two, but

00:40:57.920 --> 00:41:04.870
also comes up a lot in practice and
can lead you to completely wrong results.

00:41:05.950 --> 00:41:08.460
So I want to talk about this distinction.

00:41:09.640 --> 00:41:12.119
Independence versus
conditional independence.

00:41:14.270 --> 00:41:17.670
So, first let me write the definition
of conditional independence.

00:41:19.790 --> 00:41:22.310
So we say that,
this is the definition, but

00:41:22.310 --> 00:41:25.620
it should be kind of
an intuitive definition.

00:41:25.620 --> 00:41:28.970
We say that a and b,
this if we have events a and

00:41:28.970 --> 00:41:37.020
b, are conditionally independent.

00:41:37.020 --> 00:41:40.020
Now we can't just say
conditionally independent

00:41:40.020 --> 00:41:42.390
unless it's clear what
we're conditioning on.

00:41:42.390 --> 00:41:47.290
So to say this precisely, we would
say conditionally independent given

00:41:47.290 --> 00:41:52.920
some other event, we'll just call that C,
so C is what we're conditioning on.

00:41:52.920 --> 00:41:56.570
We say they're conditionally independent
given C, and then the definition should be

00:41:56.570 --> 00:41:59.120
obvious, just write down
the definition of independence,

00:41:59.120 --> 00:42:01.280
it's just assume everything
is conditional on C.

00:42:01.280 --> 00:42:06.134
So it's just completely analogous,
everything's conditioned on C.

00:42:06.134 --> 00:42:09.875
So I can write that down immediately.

00:42:09.875 --> 00:42:15.120
P(A intersect B given C) =
P(A given C)P(B given C).

00:42:18.741 --> 00:42:22.363
Okay, so that's the definition,
just looks like independence,

00:42:22.363 --> 00:42:24.870
except I put given C everywhere.

00:42:24.870 --> 00:42:29.470
And so a natural question then,
is does independence imply conditional

00:42:29.470 --> 00:42:34.100
independence, and does conditional
independence imply independence?

00:42:34.100 --> 00:42:36.620
So, let's talk about those two questions.

00:42:36.620 --> 00:42:41.891
So, first of all,
does conditional independence,

00:42:47.498 --> 00:42:52.664
Let's say given C, but given whatever,

00:42:52.664 --> 00:42:57.393
imply unconditional independence?

00:42:57.393 --> 00:43:00.690
And the answer is no, not in general.

00:43:00.690 --> 00:43:04.790
So if they're conditionally independent
they may or may not be independent.

00:43:04.790 --> 00:43:09.194
And there's an example that I worked out
in detail on the strategic practice, so

00:43:09.194 --> 00:43:11.721
I'll just talk about
that example briefly but

00:43:11.721 --> 00:43:14.534
you can read that example
if you haven't already.

00:43:14.534 --> 00:43:16.090
That was the chess player example.

00:43:19.120 --> 00:43:21.820
Chess opponent of unknown strength,

00:43:23.890 --> 00:43:27.160
this is a very common
situation in real life, right.

00:43:27.160 --> 00:43:31.160
You're going to, it doesn't have to be
chess obviously, that's just an example.

00:43:31.160 --> 00:43:34.360
Chess opponent of unknown, so
you can make up your own example.

00:43:34.360 --> 00:43:37.210
And that's one that I
like since I like chess.

00:43:37.210 --> 00:43:38.740
Unknown strength.

00:43:38.740 --> 00:43:41.590
So you're playing chess with
someone you've never met before.

00:43:41.590 --> 00:43:45.880
You assume you don't know that person's
rating or any information at all,

00:43:45.880 --> 00:43:48.980
so you have no idea about how
good that person is, right?

00:43:48.980 --> 00:43:53.750
Well, Suppose you play a series of chess

00:43:53.750 --> 00:43:58.600
games with that person, same person,
and then you play multiple games.

00:43:58.600 --> 00:44:01.370
Now it's possible that
after you win the first

00:44:01.370 --> 00:44:05.730
few then that person gets demoralized and
collapses and starts playing badly.

00:44:05.730 --> 00:44:08.100
Well it's possible they get mad and
they think harder and

00:44:08.100 --> 00:44:10.350
they wanna take revenge and
things like that.

00:44:10.350 --> 00:44:12.930
Ignore all that cuz I'm just
coming up with an example.

00:44:12.930 --> 00:44:16.480
So let's assume that conditional on

00:44:16.480 --> 00:44:21.270
how strong of a player that person is,
all the games are independent.

00:44:21.270 --> 00:44:22.760
That's reasonable.

00:44:24.050 --> 00:44:26.287
But that does not imply that the,

00:44:28.484 --> 00:44:32.140
That doesn't imply that the games
are unconditionally independent if you

00:44:32.140 --> 00:44:34.720
don't condition on how
strong that person is.

00:44:34.720 --> 00:44:39.020
Because if you think about it, suppose
that you win the first five games or

00:44:39.020 --> 00:44:40.470
something, okay.

00:44:40.470 --> 00:44:43.950
At that point you'd be pretty confident
that you are a better chess player than

00:44:43.950 --> 00:44:45.460
that person, right.

00:44:45.460 --> 00:44:48.350
So therefore the earlier
games give you evidence.

00:44:48.350 --> 00:44:53.550
So even though the games are seemingly
independent, the earlier games

00:44:53.550 --> 00:44:58.320
give you evidence that helps you assess
the strength of your opponent, right.

00:44:58.320 --> 00:45:02.020
So that gives you evidence that's relevant
for predicting the later outcomes.

00:45:02.020 --> 00:45:04.460
Independence would mean
that the earlier games

00:45:04.460 --> 00:45:07.460
that you played give you no information
whatsoever that helps you predict

00:45:07.460 --> 00:45:09.510
the outcomes of the later games, okay?

00:45:09.510 --> 00:45:13.830
But actually the earlier games give you
a good sense of how strong that person is,

00:45:13.830 --> 00:45:16.290
so that's the distinction.

00:45:16.290 --> 00:45:23.750
So it may happen that the games
are conditionally independent.

00:45:24.860 --> 00:45:28.790
I'll say game outcomes are conditionally
independent, but not independent.

00:45:28.790 --> 00:45:33.020
And when I say conditionally independent,

00:45:34.080 --> 00:45:37.480
I mean conditionally independent
given the strength of your opponent.

00:45:37.480 --> 00:45:41.400
So, that's one example, but
it would be good for practice for

00:45:41.400 --> 00:45:43.069
you to try to come up
with your own examples.

00:45:44.210 --> 00:45:51.030
Given strength of opponent,
but not independent.

00:45:52.650 --> 00:45:55.140
So that's an example in this direction.

